href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2023_AI_Safety_Summit">英国AI峰会</a>之类的事情，[a]全球人工智能峰会，查看AI安全，真正关注灾难性和生存风险，试图了解应了解什么样的全球机构管理AI系统，评估AI系统，审核，调节。</p><p>这正在带给世界各地的国家。我认为这是28个不同的国家将在英国AI峰会上。您拥有<a href="https://artificialintelligenceact.eu/">欧盟AI Act</a> ，它开始着眼于狭窄的AI系统，但是现在正在采用基础模型和Frontier AI系统并查看开源法规。在过去的一年中，这确实发生了全球对话。</p><p>因此，在这方面，人工智能治理进展顺利，人们正在关注。这也是很大的压力，因为突然每个人都在关注。我们必须做点什么。但是我认为对正确的态度确实有真正的兴趣，而且我认为这确实很好。因此，我很高兴看到明年的去向。是的，有关于举办全球AI峰会的讨论，然后将其制作为一个经常性的系列。因此，我认为这是人们正在关注和车轮开始转动的某种意义上的情况，这很酷。</p><h3>开放式问题<a name="open-qs"></a></h3><p><strong>丹尼尔·菲兰：</strong>好的。我想与之相关的是，您认为该领域最重要的开放问题是什么？</p><p><strong>伊丽莎白·塞格（Elizabeth Seger）：</strong>在AI治理领域？好的。因此，我认为一个很大的是计算治理，我的同事<a href="https://heim.xyz/about/">Lennart Heim</a><a href="https://www.governance.ai/team/lennart-heim">在此工作</a>。这只是在考虑计算如何试图调节谁能够开发大型模型的杠杆，甚至应该如何分发计算，以便更多的人可以分发大型模型，但基本上使用计算作为杠杆来了解谁可以访问谁谁能够开发不同类型的系统。因此，我认为这是一个巨大的研究领域，人们越来越兴趣，因为计算我们可以实际控制的有形事物之一。</p><p>我认为，围绕模型共享和开源的问题现在引起了很多关注。就像我说的那样，大的公开问题，很多辩论，这确实是一个两极分化的讨论，因此很难削减。但是很多好的团体正在为此致力于这一工作，我认为对真正找到共同点开始为此而努力的兴趣很大。我有几个情况下，我参加了小组或研讨会，我们让我们的人非常开放的来源和其他人，就像，不，让我们现在关闭整个AI系统，实际上都是频谱的两侧聚集在一起。我们尝试找到中间立场，好吧，我们在哪里同意？有什么时候我们同意吗？通常，我们可以围绕一个可能存在某些AI系统的想法达成共识，而某些模型会带来太极端的风险，以至于无法负责任地采购该模型。</p><p>这听起来可能并不像是陈述的极端，但是当您有从这种两极分化的观点中提出的人同意以下事实：有一天可能存在的模型不应该是开源的，这是一个起点，您可以从那里开始对话。到目前为止，我参加过的每个小组都必须到这一点，我们可以开始为此努力。因此，我认为这个模型共享的问题是一个很大的开放问题，大量的技术研究需要在基准测试中进行决定，何时功能太危险了？</p><p>还要了解哪些活动实际上是可以访问模型组件的不同组合的。这实际上并不完全清楚，我们需要对您实际上可以做什么的更细粒度的理解，而对于不同种类的型号，模型组件的组合，不仅为了具有安全型号的安全标准，而且确实是一个很好的 - 用于释放模型的葡萄标准，也可以保护开源的好处。如果您可以从释放某些型号组件中获得很多好处，那么您不想只拥有一条毯子“不要释放任何东西”。因此，我认为必须进行大量技术研究。</p><p>反正。是的，第二点，我认为模型共享是现在的重要讨论点。然后，随着即将举行的<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2023_AI_Safety_Summit">英国AI峰会</a>，[关于AI的国际治理结构应该是什么样的，许多不同的模型都有很多话语。是的，看到峰会发生的事情会很有趣。我认为他们不会在峰会上同意任何令人惊奇的事情。已经两天了。但是我认为，对我来说，首先，峰会的一个很大的结果是，每个人都会认识到AI Systems可能会带来极端的风险。因此，仅认识到风险。其次，一个计划正在进行，这是我们如何开始建立国际治理体系的计划，并真正构建我们何时会做出什么样的决策，以及我们如何开始将某些东西放在一起。因此，我认为这可能是三个关键的开放问题，而国际治理结构现在也很大，仅考虑到即将举行的峰会。</p><p><strong>丹尼尔·菲兰（Daniel Filan）：</strong>我想，除非我们得到这一集的编辑和转录，否则听众，<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2023_AI_Safety_Summit">英国AI峰会</a>几乎肯定会在您的过去。因此，我想听众处于一个有趣的位置，知道这一切如何以我们不这样做的方式淘汰。因此，这是广泛的野外问题。我想为您个人作为研究人员而想知道，您最感兴趣接下来是什么？</p><p><strong>伊丽莎白·塞格（Elizabeth Seger）：</strong>有趣。我的意思是，现在我一生中大部分时间都对此开源报告进行了跟进。因此，我绝对想继续研究有关模型共享的问题，并可能设定负责任的缩放策略，负责任的模型发布策略。我不太确定。我认为我现在在这个地方想了解最重要的工作需要做的地方，以及我最好的地方是鼓励其他人做某些工作像我们在谈论的那样，必须拥有更多的专业知识，例如需要更多的技术研究，以使可以访问模型组件的不同组合，或者我是否可以尝试帮助领导一些特定的研究领域？或者真正需要做的是围绕这些问题的组织能力更多。</p><p>所以不，我个人有兴趣跟上这个模型分享的讨论。我认为在这里需要做很多有趣的工作，这是一件关键的事情，目前正在围绕国际AI治理的讨论中考虑。是的，很抱歉，我在那里没有太多的明确答案，但是，是的，我仍然从发布此报告，然后在其后面出现的所有内容，然后试图感觉到下一个在哪里最重要，最有影响力的步骤，需要做什么。因此，我想您的任何听众真的很热，“哦，这是您接下来要做的”，我想，请告诉我。这将非常有帮助。</p><p><strong>丹尼尔·菲兰（Daniel Filan）：</strong>他们应该如何告诉你是否有人听说过，他们就像，哦，我需要 -</p><p><strong>伊丽莎白·塞格（Elizabeth Seger）：</strong> “我现在需要告诉她！她必须知道！”是的，所以我的意思是，我有一个<a href="https://elizabethseger.com/">网站</a>，您可以在其中找到很多联系信息，或者您总是可以在<a href="https://uk.linkedin.com/in/elizabeth-seger-ph-d-5209797b">LinkedIn</a>上找到我。这些天，我在LinkedIn上花了太多时间。而且我的电子邮件地址恰好在开源报告上。因此，如果您下载报告，我的电子邮件地址在那里。</p><p><strong>丹尼尔·菲兰（Daniel Filan）：</strong>您的网站的网址是什么？</p><p> <strong>Elizabeth Seger：</strong> <a href="https://elizabethseger.com/">Elizabethseger.com</a> 。</p><h3> x-risk的独特治理问题<a name="xrisk-different"></a></h3><p><strong>丹尼尔·菲兰：</strong>好的。好的。我想回到谈论治理的谈论，我想……所以我想这是一个以X风险为中心的播客。如果有的话，当对X风险缓解措施的担忧与您对AI治理的其他担忧相关时，您是否认为治理研究看起来有所不同？</p><p><strong>伊丽莎白·塞格（Elizabeth Seger）：</strong>嗯，这是一个很好的问题。让我们来看看。所以问题是治理研究看起来有何不同？</p><p><strong>丹尼尔·菲兰：</strong>是的。您可能会重点关注哪些不同的问题，或者您将拥有哪些不同的焦点，而不是由X-strisk担心而不是其他事情驱动？</p><p><strong>伊丽莎白·塞格（Elizabeth Seger）：</strong>所以这是我在自己的研究开发中不得不考虑很多事情，因为我没有从X风险背景的兴趣进入这一研究领域。 I came into it… I mean, honestly, I started in bioethics and then moved from bioethics looking at AI systems in healthcare and have sort of moved over into the AI governance space over a very long PhD program.所以我就在这里。</p><p> But I would say one of the things that I&#39;ve learned working in the space [that&#39;s] more interested in long-term x-risk impacts of AI and trying to prevent x-risks is really paying attention to causal pathways and really trying to be very critical about how likely a potential pathway is to actually lead to a risk. I don&#39;t know if I&#39;m explaining this very well.</p><p> Maybe a better way of saying it&#39;s like: if you have a hypothesis, or let&#39;s say you&#39;re worried about the impacts of AI systems on influence operations or impacting political campaigns, I find it really helpful to start from the hypothesis of, it won&#39;t have an impact. And really just trying to understand how that might be wrong, as opposed to trying to start from “oh, AI is going to pose a massive bio threat, or it&#39;s going to pose a massive threat to political operations” or something like that. And then almost trying to prove that conclusion.</p><p> Yeah, I don&#39;t know, I start from the opposite point and then try and think about all the ways in which I could be wrong. And I think this is really important to do, especially when you&#39;re doing x-risk research, whether it&#39;s with respect to AI or some other form of x-risk. Because I think there are a lot of people that turn off when you start talking about existential risks, they think it&#39;s too far out there, it&#39;s not really relevant to the important questions that are impacting people today, the tangible things that people are already suffering 。 And so I think it&#39;s really important to be very, very rigorous in your evaluations and have a very clear story of impact for why it is that you&#39;re doing the research you&#39;re doing and focusing on the issues that you&#39;re doing. At least that&#39;s been my experience, trying to transition into the space and work on these issues.</p><h3>技术研究助力治理<a name="tech-for-gov"></a></h3><p><strong>Daniel Filan:</strong> Another question I have, related to my audience… So I think my audience, a lot of them are technical alignment researchers and there are various things they could do, and maybe they&#39;re interested in, okay, what work could technical alignment people do that would make AI governance better? I&#39;m wondering if you have thoughts on that question.</p><p> <strong>Elizabeth Seger:</strong> Okay. Technical alignment people, AI governance better. Yeah, I mean there&#39;s a lot of work going on right now, especially within the UK government. We just set up the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/frontier-ai-taskforce-first-progress-report/frontier-ai-taskforce-first-progress-report">UK AI Task Force</a> , a government institution doing a lot of model evals and alignment research. I think if you have the technical background in alignment research, you are very much needed in the governance space. There&#39;s very often a disconnect between… I mean, I am also guilty of this. There&#39;s a disconnect between the people doing the governance research and the people who have the experience with the technology and really know the ins and outs of the technology that&#39;s being developed.</p><p> And I think if you have the inclination to work in an AI governance space and help bridge that gap, that would be incredibly valuable. And like I&#39;ve already said, some of the more technical questions, even around open-sourcing, are things that I was very, very glad to have colleagues and co-authors on the paper who have worked for AI labs and stuff before and really knew what they were talking about and could advise and help write some of the more technical aspects of the report.</p><p> So I think if you have the inclination to work in the space, to get involved with governance efforts, or even maybe some of these government institutions that are starting to pop up that are working on the boundary of AI governance and technical research, that could be a really valuable place to contribute. So I think my 2 cents off the top of my brain would be help bridge that gap.</p><p><strong>丹尼尔·菲兰：</strong>好的。伟大的。 So before we wrap up, I&#39;m wondering if there&#39;s anything that you wish I&#39;d asked but that I didn&#39;t?</p><p> <strong>Elizabeth Seger:</strong> Oh, that&#39;s a good question.不，我不这么认为。 I think we&#39;ve covered a lot of good stuff. Yeah, thank you for having me on really. I&#39;d say there&#39;s nothing in particular.这太棒了。</p><h2>根据伊丽莎白的研究<a name="following-elizabeths-research"></a></h2><p><strong>Daniel Filan:</strong> All right, so to wrap up then, if people are interested in following your research, following up on this podcast, how should they do that?</p><p> <strong>Elizabeth Seger:</strong> So I have my website, <a href="https://elizabethseger.com/">ElizabethSeger.com</a> . It sort of outlines my different ongoing research projects, has a lot of publications on it. Also, <a href="https://www.governance.ai/">GovAI&#39;s website</a> is a wealth of information [on] all things AI governance from all my great colleagues at GovAI and our affiliates. So really, yeah, there&#39;s new research reports being put out almost every week, maybe every other week, but really high quality stuff. So you can find a lot of my work on the GovAI website or my current work and past work on my own website or find me on <a href="https://uk.linkedin.com/in/elizabeth-seger-ph-d-5209797b">LinkedIn</a> . Yeah, just happy to talk more.</p><p> <strong>Daniel Filan:</strong> All right, well thank you very much for being on the podcast.</p><p> <strong>Elizabeth Seger:</strong> Great, thank you.</p><p> <strong>Daniel Filan:</strong> This episode is edited by Jack Garrett and Amber Dawn Ace helped with transcription.片头和片尾主题曲也是杰克·加勒特创作的。 Financial support for this episode was provided by the <a href="https://funds.effectivealtruism.org/funds/far-future">Long-Term Future Fund</a> and <a href="https://lightspeedgrants.org/">Lightspeed Grants</a> , along with <a href="https://patreon.com/axrpodcast">patrons</a> such as Tor Barstad, Alexey Malafeev, and Ben Weinstein-Raun. To read a transcript of this episode or to learn ho